```c
char *getLine(FILE *f)
{
    // The function of reading a line of text from a file and returning a string containing that line of text.
    char buffer[1024];
    char *p = buffer;
    char c;

    while ((c = fgetc(f))!= EOF && c!= '\n') {
        *p++ = c;
    }
    *p = '\0';

    return buffer;
}
```

This function reads a line from the file and stores it in the `buffer` array. It continues reading characters until it encounters a newline character (`'\n'`) or the end of the file (`EOF`). The `p` pointer is used to keep track of the current position in the `buffer`. After reading a line, the `p` pointer is set to the end of the buffer, and the null-terminating character (`'\0'`) is appended to the buffer. The function then returns the `buffer` array, which contains the line read from the file.

